<br>
(Oh, and someone deliver a kick under the table to the guy who said &quot;doodling ain't healthy&quot;. Fine art is just the fancy doodles that we get paid for.  Doodling is to an artist what a daily exercise routine is to an athlete.)<br>
<br>
Points to consider:<br>
a)<br>
Left hand, fingers.  They shouldn't end in a straight line.  Look at your own hand.  The fingers are different lengths, yah ?<br>
<br>
b)<br>
fingers in general.  Cool to have them separated, like a glove, but not terribly practical.  They should at least have a projecting kncuckle-guard, so his digits have a bit more protection.<br>
<br>
c)<br>
Clearly, this guy is not wearing all his gear.  He must have left his helmet at home.  He's suffering from a severe case of &quot;RoboCop Jaw&quot;.  The latin name for this affliction is Theygonnidae shooticuss meinna faceium youbetchidae.<br>
<br>
d)<br>
As art, I kinda like the little starp-on bands around his shinguards, that clearly keep his shinguards on.  I also like the &quot;R&quot; logos on his kneecaps.  In the real world, though, those kneecaps would get scraped clean pretty fast every time he kneeled, climbed, or gave someone a shot in the groin with his knee.  And, leaving the strap-bands exposed like that is just an INVITATION to have them cut, which'd allow his  his shinguard to drop to the ground and act as a cup to hold his blood as it spurted from face and shin.<br>
<br>
(Sorry... I got a bit graphic there, just to be silly.  Hope you weren't lunching on roast beef while reading this.)<br>
<br>
Good stuff-- keep it up !<br>
(Any chance of seeing a NON-violent character, like a firefighter ?  Someone in physical danger, but not dealing out death ?  Just a thought...)<br>
